"""
MKT Christ Commentary — Mark chapters 5–6
Run: python3 scripts/zc-christ-mark-5-6.py

Christological focus for this range:
- Ch 5: Christ as lord over demonic powers, death, and exclusion — the threefold authority
  over the regions beyond (Gerasenes), the isolated (bleeding woman), and death (Jairus's daughter)
- Ch 6: Christ as the rejected prophet, the true shepherd (Ezek 34), the wilderness provider
  (Exod 16; 2 Kgs 4:42-44), and the divine walker on water (Job 9:8; Ps 77:19; Exod 3:14)
- Walking on water: ego eimi as theophanic declaration, not mere identification
- The sending of the Twelve (6:7-13): extension of Christ's authority to his representatives
- John the Baptist's death (6:17-29): the forerunner's fate prefigures the Messiah's own passion
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    """Merge new_data into existing without overwriting present entries."""
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

MARK = {
  "5": {
    "1": '<p>A shadow of mission to the nations: Jesus crosses to Gentile Gerasene territory — beyond the Jewish side of the lake, beyond the boundaries of Israel\'s covenant. The movement into the "other side" (<em>peran</em>) recurs throughout Mark as a pattern of Christ going where the lost are, not waiting for them to come to him. The incarnation itself is this crossing: God into human territory, holiness into the place of uncleanness.</p>',
    "2": '<p>A revelation of God coming to the abandoned: a man from the tombs — the place of death, ritual uncleanness, and social exile — runs to meet Jesus. Christ\'s first encounter in Gentile territory is not with the respectable but with the most catastrophically isolated person imaginable. The direction of the gospel is always toward the tombs, the excluded, the unreachable (cf. Luke 19:10: "the Son of Man came to seek and save the lost").</p>',
    "3": '<p>A theme of human powerlessness before spiritual bondage: the man cannot be bound, no human strength can contain him. The catalog of failed chains and fetters establishes that what holds the man is beyond human remediation. Only the one stronger than the strong man (3:27) can enter the strong man\'s house and free his captives. Christ comes precisely to where human power ends.</p>',
    "4": '<p>A theme of the failed human remedies for spiritual bondage: the escalating futility — chained, broke chains, fettered, broke fetters, no one strong enough to subdue him — frames the entrance of the one who subdues all things (Phil 3:21: Christ "will transform our lowly bodies so that they will be like his glorious body, by the power that enables him to bring everything under his control"). What no man could do, Christ does with a word.</p>',
    "5": '<p>A revelation of what spiritual bondage looks like: night and day, among the tombs, crying out, cutting himself — this is the condition of the one who belongs to the unclean powers. The image is extreme but representative of the condition of all who are under the dominion of death and sin (Eph 2:1-3: "dead in your transgressions and sins"). Christ enters this landscape not to observe it but to end it.</p>',
    "6": '<p>A revelation of Christ\'s lordship over the demonic: "he ran and fell on his knees in front of him" — the demon-controlled man performs the gesture of submission to Christ before a word is spoken. Even the forces of spiritual darkness bow before him. Philippians 2:10 ("at the name of Jesus every knee should bow, in heaven and on earth and under the earth") is enacted here in microcosm: the knee of the demonized is the first to bow.</p>',
    "7": '<p>A direct revelation from demonic testimony: "Jesus, Son of the Most High God" — the demons recognize Jesus\'s identity before the disciples do. The title "Son of the Most High God" (<em>huios tou theou tou hypsistou</em>) uses the Gentile form of the divine name (the <em>El Elyon</em> of Melchizedek and the Gentile traditions, Gen 14:18-22), suggesting recognition across the boundaries of Jewish messianic categories. The tormentor recognizes the one who has authority to torment the tormentors.</p>',
    "8": '<p>A theme of Christ\'s authority over impure spirits: "Come out of this man, you impure spirit!" — the same command as at Capernaum (1:25-26), now in Gentile territory. The scope of Christ\'s exorcistic authority knows no geographic boundary. Colossians 2:15 ("he disarmed the powers and authorities, he made a public spectacle of them, triumphing over them by the cross") identifies the cross as the definitive exorcism; these Galilean and Decapolis exorcisms are signs of what the cross accomplishes.</p>',
    "9": '<p>A revelation of Christ\'s authority over named demonic powers: "My name is Legion" — Christ compels the disclosure of identity. In the ancient world, knowing and naming a spirit gave power over it; here it is Christ who asks and the demons who must answer. The name Legion (a Roman military unit of ~6,000) also underscores the scale of the bondage. Christ\'s authority extends not just to individual spirits but to organized demonic assemblies (Eph 6:12: "the powers and authorities, the spiritual forces of evil in the heavenly realms").</p>',
    "10": '<p>A theme of demonic subjection to Christ\'s judgment: the demons beg "again and again not to send them out of the area" — the request implies they know they are under Christ\'s jurisdiction and cannot resist his decision. Their begging is itself a declaration of his authority. The cosmic powers that oppose God beg for terms from the one who has authority over them — an anticipation of the final judgment when all enemies are placed under Christ\'s feet (1 Cor 15:25).</p>',
    "11": '<p>A theme of providential setting: the nearby herd of pigs — a Gentile detail that would mark this as unclean territory for any Jewish reader — is the instrument through which the man\'s liberation becomes visible to the community. God uses what is present in the place he enters. The story\'s Gentile context (pigs, Decapolis) makes it a foreshadowing of the Gentile mission in which Christ\'s liberating power will operate.</p>',
    "12": '<p>A revelation that Christ\'s presence is inescapable judgment for the demonic: even their request to go into the pigs is a petition — they cannot act without his permission. The demons\' request to enter unclean animals in unclean territory is the irony of powers that sought dominion being confined to the lowest place. Christ\'s consent to their request gives them what they asked for, which leads to their destruction — a pattern of divine permission that serves divine purpose.</p>',
    "13": '<p>A theme of liberation through apparent loss: the pigs rush into the lake; the local community loses an economic asset; the man gains his freedom. The cost of liberation is real — the pigs, the economic disruption — but the value of the person freed outweighs it (Luke 15:7: "there will be more rejoicing in heaven over one sinner who repents than over ninety-nine righteous persons who do not need to repent"). Christ consistently treats human restoration as worth economic and social disruption.</p>',
    "14": '<p>A theme of the world\'s response to Christ\'s liberation: the pig-herders run to report, the townspeople come to see. The news of a miraculous event draws witnesses. But what they find (v.15) frightens them rather than drawing them. The pattern anticipates Gethsemane and the trial: witnesses to extraordinary events about Christ respond with fear, flight, or hostility rather than faith.</p>',
    "15": '<p>A revelation of what Christ\'s salvation looks like: the formerly demonized man "sitting there, dressed and in his right mind" — three particulars of restoration. Sitting (not running and crying out), clothed (not naked and unrestrained), in his right mind (not controlled by alien powers). This is the image of salvation: the humanity that was lost to bondage, restored to its God-given dignity. The observers\' fear in the face of this restoration is the world\'s characteristic response to grace it did not expect and cannot categorize.</p>',
    "16": '<p>A theme of witness to Christ\'s power: those who had seen it told what happened — to the man and to the pigs. The double witness (the human restoration, the dramatic sign of the pigs) is offered to the community. The community will reject it (v.17). The pattern of witnessed miracle followed by community rejection anticipates the rejection Jesus will face more broadly.</p>',
    "17": '<p>A theme of the world\'s rejection of Christ: "they began to plead with Jesus to leave their region" — having seen the miracle and heard the testimony, the Gerasene community asks Jesus to leave. The liberation of the man is less valuable to them than the disruption of the status quo. The same structure recurs throughout Mark: Nazareth (6:3), Jerusalem (ch.14-15). The world consistently prefers its own disordered familiarity to the disruptive presence of the one who makes all things new.</p>',
    "18": '<p>A theme of the redeemed clinging to the Redeemer: the healed man "begged to go with him" — the natural response of one whose life has been restored. The desire to remain with Jesus is the proper movement of the saved soul toward its Savior. But Christ redirects this desire into mission (v.19), showing that the love for Christ is expressed through witness, not simply through accompaniment.</p>',
    "19": '<p>A revelation of Christ commissioning the first Gentile witness: "Go home to your own people and tell them how much the Lord has done for you, and how he has had mercy on you." The first person explicitly commissioned to testify about Jesus in Mark is a Gentile, in Gentile territory, before the formal sending of the Twelve (6:7). The Gentile mission is not an afterthought to Mark\'s Gospel; it begins here, commissioned by Jesus himself. "How much the Lord has done" — <em>ho kyrios</em> in the mouth of Jesus refers to God; the man will proclaim "how much Jesus had done" (v.20), equating the two.</p>',
    "20": '<p>A revelation of the Gentile mission as proclamation of Christ: the man "began to tell in the Decapolis how much Jesus had done for him." He substitutes "Jesus" for "the Lord" (v.19) — making the equation that the Christology of the NT will develop: what God does, Jesus does. The Decapolis proclamation anticipates the scope of the NT mission to Gentiles (Acts 1:8: "to the ends of the earth"). All were amazed — the Gentile world\'s response to Christ\'s power is available to it from the beginning.</p>',
    "21": '<p>A theme of Christ\'s continual accessibility: he crosses back to the Jewish side and immediately "a large crowd gathered around him." The one who had gone to the far Gentile shore returns to be available to the Jewish crowd — the movement between communities (Jewish/Gentile, religious leader/hemorrhaging outcast) is the pattern of his universal mission.</p>',
    "22": '<p>A revelation of Christ as the hope of every level of society: Jairus, a synagogue ruler — a person of religious authority, social standing — "fell at his feet." The posture of humility before Christ crosses social boundaries. The same posture as the Gerasene demoniac (v.6) and the hemorrhaging woman (v.33): all who come to Jesus in genuine need adopt the posture of dependence. Rank counts for nothing; need counts for everything.</p>',
    "23": '<p>A theme of death as the ultimate problem that only Christ can solve: "my little daughter is dying" — the father\'s earnest pleading (the same verb, <em>parakalein</em>, as in v.10 where the demons plead) expresses the absolute limit of paternal love and human power. Death is the one problem before which all human competence fails. The Gospel of Mark structures this encounter so that it will escalate from dying to dead before Christ acts — making the demonstration of his power over death unambiguous.</p>',
    "24": '<p>A theme of Christ going to the place of need: "Jesus went with him" — the uncomplicated willingness to accompany the desperate father. No hesitation, no negotiation, no preconditions. The divine willingness to go to the place of human need is the pattern of the incarnation itself: the Word came to where we are (John 1:14).</p>',
    "25": '<p>A theme of persistent suffering that finds its end only in Christ: twelve years of hemorrhaging — a period of chronic, unresolvable affliction. The woman\'s condition has been continuous, exhausting, and isolating (ritual uncleanness under Lev 15:25-27 cut her off from communal worship and social contact). The length of suffering intensifies the significance of the healing. Christ does not require that suffering be brief before he addresses it.</p>',
    "26": '<p>A theme of the exhaustion of human remedies: "she had suffered a great deal under the care of many doctors and had spent all she had, yet instead of getting better she grew worse." The catalog of failed human attempts — money spent, doctors consulted, condition worsened — frames Christ as the one resource that succeeds where all others fail. This is not anti-medicine but narrative theology: when all human resources are exhausted, Christ remains.</p>',
    "27": '<p>A theme of faith reaching toward Christ from behind, anonymously: she came "behind him" and touched his cloak. The anonymous, unacknowledged approach — from the back of the crowd, touching clothing rather than the person — is the faith of those who dare not present themselves directly. Christ meets this faith too, and will not let it remain anonymous (v.32). No one who touches Christ in genuine faith goes unrecognized by him.</p>',
    "28": '<p>A theme of the faith that reaches toward Christ: "if I just touch his clothes, I will be healed." The reasoning is not superstitious (as if the garment contained magic) but typological: she has heard what Jesus does and believes that contact with him — even indirect, even marginal — is sufficient. This is the structure of all saving faith: confidence that Christ himself, touched by faith, is adequate to the need.</p>',
    "29": '<p>A revelation of the immediate efficacy of faith-contact with Christ: "immediately her bleeding stopped and she felt in her body that she was freed from her suffering." The healing is total, immediate, and physically felt. The word "freed" (<em>iaomai</em>) — healed, made whole — is the vocabulary of salvation and restoration. Faith that reaches Christ always receives what it reaches for.</p>',
    "30": '<p>A revelation of Christ as the source of healing power: "power had gone out from him" (<em>dynamis ex autou exelthyousa</em>) — Christ\'s healing is not performance but emanation; something went out from him. The vocabulary suggests that Christ is the reservoir from which healing flows, not merely an agent through whom it passes. This is consistent with Colossians 1:19 ("God was pleased to have all his fullness dwell in him") and John 1:16 ("from his fullness we have all received").</p>',
    "31": '<p>A theme of the disciples\' failure to perceive what Christ perceives: "You see the people crowding against you, and yet you can ask, \'Who touched me?\'" — the disciples see crowd pressure where Jesus perceives faith. The difference is not physical but spiritual: Jesus distinguishes the touch of faith from accidental contact. The disciples will repeatedly miss what Jesus sees; faith is the instrument of perception that they do not yet fully possess.</p>',
    "32": '<p>A revelation of Christ\'s personal attention to the one who touched him in faith: "he kept looking around to see who had done it." The Son of God, surrounded by thousands, searches for one person — the one who touched him in faith. No one who comes to Christ in genuine faith becomes one of the anonymous crowd to him. He knows his own (John 10:14), and seeks out each one.</p>',
    "33": '<p>A theme of the movement from anonymous faith to confessed faith: the woman "knowing what had happened to her, came and fell at his feet and, trembling with fear, told him the whole truth." She had touched him anonymously; now she falls at his feet and confesses. The pattern is the same in every genuine encounter with Christ: anonymous reaching becomes named, confessed discipleship. The one who meets Christ in faith cannot remain hidden.</p>',
    "34": '<p>A direct revelation of Christ granting peace and wholeness: "Daughter, your faith has healed you. Go in peace and be freed from your suffering." The address "Daughter" is the familial declaration — she is adopted into the family of the one who heals her. "Go in peace" (<em>hypage eis eirēnēn</em>) is the priestly blessing formula (cf. Judg 18:6; 1 Sam 1:17), here given by the Great High Priest. "Be freed from your suffering" — the perfect, complete, future-guaranteed liberation is Christ\'s gift to the one who came in faith.</p>',
    "35": '<p>A revelation of Christ as the answer to death, not just illness: while Jesus is still speaking about the healed woman, news arrives that Jairus\'s daughter has died. The escalation from dying to dead is the story\'s Christological core: Christ is not limited to healing the sick; his authority extends over death itself. The timing — "while Jesus was still speaking" — underscores that the power at work in the woman\'s healing and the power that will raise Jairus\'s daughter are the same power.</p>',
    "36": '<p>A direct revelation of Christ calling for faith against death: "Don\'t be afraid; just believe." The command is addressed to Jairus, whose circumstances have just become worst-case. The word for "believe" (<em>pisteue</em>) — present imperative — means "keep on believing"; the faith already present must persist through the news of death. Christ\'s call to faith against death is the call of the gospel itself: believe the one who says "I am the resurrection" (John 11:25) even when death has arrived.</p>',
    "37": '<p>A theme of Christ preparing selected witnesses for a resurrection revelation: Peter, James, and John — the inner three — are taken with Jesus to the house of death. They will be the witnesses to three defining Christological events: the resurrection of Jairus\'s daughter (here), the transfiguration (9:2), and Gethsemane (14:33). The narrowing of witness is not exclusion but preparation: these men will be foundational witnesses for what the church will believe about Jesus.</p>',
    "38": '<p>A theme of Christ entering the house of death: "Jesus saw a commotion, with people crying and wailing loudly" — professional mourners and weeping family have gathered because they believe the girl is dead. Jesus\'s entrance into this house of mourning is the movement of the incarnation in miniature: the Lord of life entering the place where death has established itself. He goes where death has already claimed its victim.</p>',
    "39": '<p>A revelation of Christ transforming the category of death: "The child is not dead but asleep" — the language anticipates the NT transformation of death for those who are in Christ. 1 Thessalonians 4:14 ("those who have fallen asleep in him") uses the same sleep-language because of the resurrection that Christ demonstrates here. Death is not annihilated but reclassified: for those in Christ, it becomes the sleep from which resurrection awakens them. The mourners laugh because they do not know the resurrection; the gospel calls people to believe before they see it.</p>',
    "40": '<p>A theme of the world\'s contempt for resurrection hope: "they laughed at him" — the professional mourners (and presumably others) mock Jesus\'s reclassification of death as sleep. The laughter is the world\'s characteristic response to resurrection: 1 Corinthians 15:12 records the same skepticism ("how can some of you say there is no resurrection of the dead?"). Christ does not engage the mockery but puts it out of the room and proceeds to demonstrate the truth of what he has declared.</p>',
    "42": '<p>A direct type of the resurrection: "immediately the girl stood up and began to walk around." Her resurrection is a direct anticipation of the general resurrection and a type of Christ\'s own: the one who raises the dead will himself be raised (1 Cor 15:20: "Christ has indeed been raised from the dead, the firstfruits of those who have fallen asleep"). Jairus\'s daughter and Lazarus (John 11) and the widow\'s son (Luke 7:11-17) are preliminary signs of the resurrection that Christ will accomplish for all who are in him.</p>',
    "43": '<p>A theme of the Messianic Secret at the resurrection miracle: "give strict orders not to let anyone know about this" — the most astonishing miracle so far (a raised-from-the-dead child, multiple witnesses, a synagogue ruler as recipient) immediately placed under silence. The Secret pattern reaches its most paradoxical moment here: how does one conceal a raised child? The command cannot succeed practically, but it establishes that Jesus defines the terms of the messianic revelation. The resurrection will be proclaimed — but on Christ\'s terms, not the crowd\'s.</p>'
  },
  "6": {
    "1": '<p>A theme of the rejected prophet: "Jesus left there and went to his hometown" — the return to Nazareth that will end in rejection (v.3-4). The theme of the prophet rejected by his own people runs through the entire OT prophetic tradition (Jer 12:6; 1 Kgs 19:10) and is applied to Jesus explicitly (v.4) and to the whole pattern of Israel\'s history (Luke 13:34; Acts 7:52). The hometown rejection is not incidental; it is the pattern of how God\'s messengers are received by those who think they already know who they are.</p>',
    "2": '<p>A theme of the world confronting Christ without accepting him: "Where did this man get these things?" — the crowd in Nazareth acknowledges the wisdom and the miracles but cannot integrate them with their knowledge of the man. They recognize the extraordinary but refuse its implication. The confrontation with Christ always demands a decision: the evidence is available, but those who refuse it do not lose the evidence, they merely suppress its claim (Rom 1:18-20).</p>',
    "3": '<p>A direct revelation of the offense of the incarnation: "Isn\'t this the carpenter? Isn\'t this Mary\'s son?" — the offense (<em>eskandalizonto</em>) is taken at the very fact of incarnation: God known as a local tradesman, the eternal Word identified as a specific village craftsman. Paul identifies this as the pattern: "God chose the lowly things of this world and the despised things" (1 Cor 1:28). The incarnation is permanently scandalous to those who expect divine power to present itself in impressive human form.</p>',
    "4": '<p>A direct revelation of Christ placing himself in the prophetic tradition: "A prophet is not without honor except in his own town, among his relatives and in his own home." Jesus\'s self-identification as a prophet is significant — not the whole truth (he is more than a prophet) but the frame for understanding rejection. The prophetic tradition of rejection (Elijah in Israel, Jeremiah in Judah) culminates in Jesus\'s own rejection and crucifixion (Luke 13:33: "no prophet can die outside Jerusalem"). The pattern is old; the final instance of it is new.</p>',
    "5": '<p>A revelation of faith as the condition for receiving Christ\'s power: "he could not do any miracles there" — not because his power was absent but because unbelief provides no opening for it. The limitation is not ontological (Christ\'s inherent ability) but relational: miracles are given to those who receive the giver. The refusal of faith is simultaneously a refusal of the gift. Unbelief is not neutral; it closes the hand that would receive the healing.</p>',
    "6": '<p>A revelation of Christ\'s response to unbelief: "he was amazed at their lack of faith" (<em>ethaumazen</em> — the same word used of Pilate\'s amazement at Jesus\'s silence, 15:5). Christ is amazed in Mark twice: at the centurion\'s great faith (Matt 8:10) and at Nazareth\'s great faithlessness. The two poles of response to him — faith that exceeds expectation, unbelief that exceeds expectation — are both remarkable. Unbelief is not normal; it is an astonishment.</p>',
    "7": '<p>A revelation of Christ extending his authority through representatives: "he gave them authority over impure spirits" — the Twelve receive what Christ has: authority to cast out demons (cf. 3:14-15). The apostolic commission is the extension of Christ\'s own ministry, not a separate enterprise. This prefigures the church\'s mission: the authority to preach, teach, and minister in Christ\'s name is derived from his own authority and exercised as his representatives. The Twelve are not acting independently; they are acting as agents of the one who sent them.</p>',
    "8": '<p>A theme of radical dependence on God\'s provision: "take nothing for the journey except a staff — no bread, no bag, no money." The instruction strips the missionaries of self-sufficiency so that their provision must come from God and from the hospitality of those who receive the message. This is the pattern of the Exodus (God provided manna) and of Jesus\'s own teaching (Matt 6:25-34: "do not worry about your life"). The kingdom comes through those who trust the King to provide for his emissaries.</p>',
    "9": '<p>A theme of simple material preparation in mission: sandals and one tunic — the minimum for a journey. The instruction establishes that the mission is not about the missionaries\' comfort or display. The messenger\'s simplicity is itself a sign: the kingdom does not arrive with impressive apparatus but through those who carry only the message. Paul will articulate this as the pattern of apostolic weakness through which Christ\'s power is made perfect (2 Cor 12:9-10).</p>',
    "10": '<p>A theme of focused mission over rapid movement: "whenever you enter a house, stay there until you leave that town." The instruction values depth of engagement over breadth of coverage. The missionary who stays in one house builds relationship rather than collecting contacts. Christ\'s own ministry was characterized by intensive engagement with specific people and places, not a broadcast approach. The quality of the gospel\'s reception matters; hasty movement prevents it.</p>',
    "11": '<p>A theme of the gospel\'s judgment on rejection: "shake the dust off your feet as a testimony against them" — the dust-shaking was a gesture of prophetic warning, declaring that the messengers bear no responsibility for the city\'s rejection (cf. Acts 13:51). The gospel\'s offer is not indiscriminate nor permanent; those who reject it bear the weight of that rejection. The "testimony against them" (<em>eis martyrion autois</em>) will be the evidence at judgment that they heard and refused (Matt 11:20-24).</p>',
    "12": '<p>A direct revelation of the apostolic message as Christ\'s own: "they went out and preached that people should repent" — the same message as John the Baptist (1:4) and Jesus himself (1:15). The continuity of the message across John, Jesus, and the Twelve establishes that the kingdom\'s call is consistent: repentance is the response that the gospel has always demanded. The Twelve are not preaching something new but extending the same call that has been present since the beginning of the Gospel.</p>',
    "13": '<p>A revelation of the apostolic ministry as extension of Christ\'s ministry: "they drove out many demons and anointed many sick people with oil and healed them" — exorcism and healing, exactly what Jesus had been doing (1:25-27, 1:31, 1:34). The anointing with oil appears in James 5:14 as a continuing church practice. The mission of the Twelve is not separate from Christ\'s mission but its replication through his representatives. The church\'s ministry participates in and extends the ministry that Christ himself began.</p>',
    "14": '<p>A theme of the world\'s confused attempts to categorize Christ: Herod\'s conclusion that Jesus is John the Baptist raised from the dead places Jesus in the category of the miraculous-returned. The identification reflects a theology of divine power returning through extraordinary figures — not wrong in its register (Jesus is indeed a figure of divine power) but wrong in its specific identification. The world always tries to place Jesus in a known category; the gospel insists he exceeds all categories.</p>',
    "15": '<p>A theme of inadequate identifications of Christ: "He is Elijah" or "one of the prophets" — the same identifications offered at Caesarea Philippi (8:28). Elijah was the expected forerunner; the prophets were figures of divine agency. Both are true in limited ways (Jesus is a prophet and more, 6:4; John was Elijah and Jesus acknowledged it, 9:13), but neither captures who Jesus is. Every partial identification is simultaneously a recognition and a misrecognition.</p>',
    "16": '<p>A theme of guilt before righteous judgment: Herod\'s conviction that John is raised functions as a moral verdict against himself — he has silenced the righteous man\'s voice, and now the voice seems to be speaking again. The conscience that knows it has wronged the innocent cannot escape the suspicion that judgment will come. Herod\'s theological mistake (John raised rather than Jesus) is the product of a guilty conscience, not a calm theological assessment.</p>',
    "17": '<p>A theme of the prophet imprisoned for speaking truth to power: John arrested because he confronted Herod\'s adultery. The pattern of the righteous prophet imprisoned by corrupt authority will repeat itself in Jesus\'s own trial and imprisonment (14:46, 14:53). John\'s fate is the prototype of Jesus\'s fate; the forerunner endures what the Messiah will endure. The prophet who announces the kingdom is always unwelcome in the halls of worldly power.</p>',
    "18": '<p>A theme of the prophet speaking truth at personal cost: "It is not lawful for you to have your brother\'s wife" — John\'s courage before Herod mirrors the prophetic tradition of Elijah before Ahab (1 Kgs 18:17-18), Nathan before David (2 Sam 12:7), and Isaiah before Ahaz. The willingness to name the ruler\'s sin is the mark of the genuine prophet. Jesus will do the same: naming the temple establishment\'s corruption (11:17), the scribes\' exploitation (12:40), the high priest\'s hypocrisy (14:62). The true witness of Christ does not protect itself by silence before power.</p>',
    "19": '<p>A theme of the world\'s antagonism toward the righteous voice: Herodias "nursed a grudge" (<em>enichen</em>) against John and wanted to kill him. The world\'s hatred of righteousness is the same hatred that will target Jesus (3:6: the Pharisees and Herodians conspire against him "as early as" the Galilean ministry). The righteous voice provokes the desire to silence it; what was true of John was true of Christ; what is true of Christ is true of his church (John 15:18-20).</p>',
    "20": '<p>A theme of the conflicted response to righteousness: Herod "feared John and protected him, knowing him to be a righteous and holy man." The ambivalent response — protecting the prophet, yet being unable to act on what the prophet says — is the pattern of those who are near the kingdom but not in it. Herod will yield to social pressure and execute John (v.26-27) as Pilate will yield to social pressure and execute Jesus. The one who acknowledges righteousness without submitting to it is more culpable, not less.</p>',
    "21": '<p>A theme of worldly power creating the occasion for injustice: Herod\'s birthday banquet — the occasion of his oath and his compliance with Herodias\'s demand. The setting (a royal court, an elaborate feast, military commanders and nobles as audience) is the social pressure system within which the unjust verdict will be made. Worldly honor dynamics — the oath before important guests, the refusal to lose face — become the mechanism of the prophet\'s death. The same dynamics will operate in the Sanhedrin (14:55) and Pilate\'s court (15:15).</p>',
    "22": '<p>A theme of the oath made by worldly power: "Ask me for anything you want, and I\'ll give it to you" — Herod\'s reckless promise, made in the context of a performance that pleased him. The formula echoes the royal generosity of Esther 5:3 (King Ahasuerus to Esther: "up to half my kingdom"). The promise is legally binding in the world of honor-culture oath-making. The accidental oath — made for the wrong reasons, held to for the wrong reasons — becomes the legal mechanism of execution.</p>',
    "23": '<p>A theme of oath-keeping that serves injustice: "Whatever you ask I will give you, up to half my kingdom." The half-kingdom promise is hyperbole of the royal promise genre but binds Herod more completely than he intended. The problem is not oath-keeping as such (oaths matter, Eccl 5:2-5) but an oath made rashly in a context designed to exploit it. The series of decisions that follows is shaped by the social compulsion of the oath rather than by justice.</p>',
    "24": '<p>A theme of evil counsel leading to the innocent\'s death: the daughter goes to her mother for advice and receives an evil request. The consultation scene shows that the execution of John is not impulsive but deliberate: Herodias has been waiting for this moment (v.19: she "nursed a grudge"). The death of the righteous prophet is not the product of passion but of long-cultivated hatred looking for the right moment. The same patient malice will orchestrate the plot against Jesus (14:1-2).</p>',
    "25": '<p>A theme of urgency in executing the unjust: the girl returns "at once" and demands John\'s head "right now" (<em>exautēs</em>). The haste in killing the righteous — wanting it done before circumstances can change — is the same urgency the chief priests will show in arranging Jesus\'s arrest (14:1: "they were looking for some sly way to arrest Jesus and kill him") and in bringing him to Pilate early in the morning (15:1). Evil against the righteous is conducted with haste.</p>',
    "26": '<p>A theme of authority bowing to social pressure: "the king was greatly distressed, but because of his oaths and his dinner guests, he did not want to refuse her." Herod knows the execution is unjust; he is "greatly distressed" (<em>perilypous</em> — the same word used of Jesus in Gethsemane, 14:34: "my soul is overwhelmed with sorrow to the point of death"). The parallel is not coincidental: the one who wrongly executes the prophet and the one who is wrongly executed share a vocabulary of anguish. Herod\'s distress is the mirror of Jesus\'s sorrow; both men face a death they do not want, for different reasons.</p>',
    "27": '<p>A theme of the righteous killed by official power for political reasons: the executioner (<em>spekoulator</em> — a Latin loanword for a military scout or executioner) is sent "immediately." The machinery of state power — soldier, order, beheading, presentation of the head — is the same machinery that will be directed against Jesus: the soldiers of the Praetorium (15:16-20), the flogging (15:15), the cross (15:24). John\'s death is a dress rehearsal for Christ\'s, executed by the same kind of authority through the same kind of officials.</p>',
    "28": '<p>A type of Christ\'s death: John\'s head delivered "on a dish" is the gruesome particular that marks the forerunner\'s end as violent, public, and official. He dies as a result of speaking truth to power; his body is presented as a trophy. This is the fate of the messenger who precedes the Messiah. The type is structural: the one who "prepared the way" is killed; the one whose way is prepared will be killed. The forerunner\'s death foreshadows the Messiah\'s death (9:13: "they did to him whatever they wished, just as it is written about him").</p>',
    "29": '<p>A type of Christ\'s burial: "John\'s disciples came and took his body and laid it in a tomb" — the burial of the righteous executed man by his followers. The same pattern will repeat exactly for Jesus: Joseph of Arimathea and the women take the body and place it in a tomb (15:45-46). The forerunner\'s burial anticipates the Messiah\'s burial; each detail of John\'s end (imprisonment, execution, body taken by disciples, laid in a tomb) will be replicated in Jesus\'s end.</p>',
    "30": '<p>A theme of Christ receiving the report of his apostles\' mission: the Twelve return and report "all they had done and taught." The apostolic mission is accountable to Christ; the missionaries report back to the one who sent them. This pattern of commission-mission-report is the structure of NT church mission (Acts 14:27: the Antioch church gathers to hear "all that God had done through them"). The mission belongs to Christ; the missionaries are stewards of what was given to them.</p>',
    "31": '<p>A revelation of Christ\'s pastoral care for the mission workers: "Come with me by yourselves to a quiet place and get some rest." The command to rest — to withdraw from the press of ministry for renewal — is itself a revelation of what Christ thinks about his servants. He is not an exploitative master who demands output without care for the workers. Sabbath rest was God\'s gift from creation (Gen 2:2-3); Christ extends this gift to those who labor in his name.</p>',
    "32": '<p>A theme of the solitary place as the place of renewal with Christ: "they went away by themselves in a boat to a solitary place." The withdrawal to the wilderness/<em>erēmos</em> with Jesus recurs in Mark: the baptism (1:12), prayer (1:35), and now the rest with the Twelve. The "solitary place" is not absence of God but the place where God can be heard. The pattern of Elijah (1 Kgs 19:4-9: the exhausted prophet fed in the wilderness by the angel of the Lord) is present.</p>',
    "33": '<p>A theme of the impossibility of withdrawing from human need: the crowd runs ahead and arrives before the boat. The people\'s persistence in following Jesus mirrors the drawing power he will describe: "when I am lifted up from the earth, I will draw all people to myself" (John 12:32). Need pursues Christ; the crowd\'s running ahead is the pattern of the world\'s desperate seeking — the hunger that will not let the one who can feed it simply rest.</p>',
    "34": '<p>A direct revelation of Christ as the true shepherd fulfilling Ezekiel\'s promise: "he had compassion on them, because they were like sheep without a shepherd." Ezekiel 34 is God\'s indictment of Israel\'s unfaithful shepherds (the rulers who exploit rather than feed the flock) and his promise of the true shepherd: "I myself will search for my sheep... I will rescue them... I will tend them in a good pasture... I will shepherd the flock with justice" (Ezek 34:11-16). The divine promise culminates: "I will set one shepherd over them, my servant David" (Ezek 34:23). Jesus looking on the crowd "like sheep without a shepherd" is the fulfillment of this promise: the one shepherd whom God promised has arrived.</p>',
    "35": '<p>A theme of the disciples seeing practical problems where Christ sees kingdom opportunity: "This is a remote place, and it\'s already very late" — a correct assessment of the logistical situation, offered as a reason for the crowd to be sent away. The disciples measure the situation by available resources; Jesus measures it by the power present in his own person. The gap between their diagnosis and his is the gap between human calculation and faith in the one who multiplies.</p>',
    "36": '<p>A theme of compassion leading to provision: "send the people away so they can go buy food" — the disciples\' solution is dispersal; Christ\'s solution is provision. The contrast establishes the pattern of Christ\'s response to human need: where others disperse, he gathers; where others acknowledge lack, he supplies. The feeding miracle is the practical demonstration of the eschatological banquet (Isa 25:6-8; Luke 13:29; Rev 19:9) in which Christ hosts all who come to him.</p>',
    "37": '<p>A type of Christ providing where human resources are impossibly inadequate: "you give them something to eat" — the impossible command. The disciples calculate the cost (six months\' wages) and declare it beyond reach. The same structure appears in 2 Kings 4:42-44: Elisha\'s servant objects that twenty loaves cannot feed a hundred men; Elisha says "give it to the people to eat" and there is surplus. Jesus\'s command is the Elisha-type command, but on a scale (5,000+) that exceeds even that miracle, revealing that the one making the command exceeds the prophet.</p>',
    "38": '<p>A theme of Christ working with what is given: "five [loaves] and two fish" — the human inventory is offered and Christ accepts it. The pattern is consistent: the inadequate offering given to Christ becomes adequate through his blessing. The five loaves and two fish are not nothing; they are the disciples\' entire supply, offered at Christ\'s request. The surrender of the insufficient to Christ is the act of faith that precedes miraculous provision.</p>',
    "39": '<p>A theme of the orderly provision of God: Jesus directing the crowd to "sit down in groups on the green grass" — the organized seating on green grass evokes Psalm 23:2 ("he makes me lie down in green pastures"). The organization of the crowd echoes Exodus 18:21 (Jethro\'s advice to Moses to organize Israel in groups of thousands, hundreds, fifties, and tens). The feeding miracle is a new-exodus event: Christ the shepherd feeds the flock in the wilderness as God fed Israel in the desert.</p>',
    "40": '<p>A theme of the Exodus pattern in Christ\'s provision: the groups of hundreds and fifties echo Moses organizing Israel into units (Exod 18:21-25; Num 31:14). The wilderness setting, the organized groups, and the miraculous food provision together constitute a new-exodus typology: Christ is the new Moses, leading a new Israel through the wilderness to the kingdom. The five thousand on green grass are the people of God in the wilderness, fed by their shepherd-leader.</p>',
    "41": '<p>A type of the Eucharist and the eschatological banquet: Jesus took the loaves, looked up to heaven, gave thanks (<em>eulogēsen</em>), broke the loaves, and gave them to the disciples to distribute. The four actions (take, bless, break, give) are the four actions of the Last Supper (14:22-23) and the two Emmaus disciples\' recognition of the risen Christ (Luke 24:30-31). Elijah\'s and Elisha\'s multiplications (1 Kgs 17:14-16; 2 Kgs 4:42-44) are the OT type; the Last Supper and the eschatological banquet are the fulfillment. Christ is simultaneously the host and the bread.</p>',
    "42": '<p>A direct fulfillment of Psalm 22:26 and Psalm 107:9: "they all ate and were satisfied" (<em>eχortasthēsan</em> — filled to satisfaction). Psalm 22:26: "The poor will eat and be satisfied." Psalm 107:9: "he satisfies the thirsty and fills the hungry with good things." The wilderness feeding is Christ\'s fulfillment of the Psalter\'s promise that God provides for those who have nothing. "All" ate — no one in the crowd was left hungry. The eschatological feast will be characterized by the same completeness: no one who comes will be turned away (John 6:37).</p>',
    "43": '<p>A type of the abundance of Christ\'s provision: twelve basketfuls of leftovers — more than the five loaves and two fish with which they began. The twelve baskets have obvious symbolic weight for Israel (twelve tribes), suggesting that Christ\'s provision for Israel\'s covenant community is superabundant. The surplus is not waste but sign: "to him who is able to do immeasurably more than all we ask or imagine" (Eph 3:20). The baskets of surplus are the visible testimony to the excess of Christ\'s provision.</p>',
    "44": '<p>A type of Christ as the new Moses feeding Israel in the wilderness: five thousand men — a number of Israel-scale (Moses organized Israel in units; Exod 18). The wilderness feeding of five thousand echoes the manna provision of Exodus 16, which Jesus will explicitly identify in John 6:32-35 ("it is my Father who gives you the true bread from heaven... I am the bread of life"). The feeding miracle is not merely a humanitarian act but a typological claim: the one who feeds five thousand in the wilderness is the fulfillment of Moses and the manna.</p>',
    "45": '<p>A theme of Christ deliberately withdrawing after a moment of potential misidentification: Jesus sends the disciples ahead and dismisses the crowd "immediately" after the feeding (John 6:14-15 explains: the crowd wanted to make him king by force). The withdrawal is the Messianic Secret in action at a moment of maximum Messianic enthusiasm. He will not be made the kind of king the crowd wants; his kingship comes through the cross, not through the crowd\'s acclamation.</p>',
    "46": '<p>A revelation of Christ in intercessory prayer: "after leaving them, he went up on a mountainside to pray." The pattern of withdrawal to pray after significant ministry recurs in Mark (1:35, 6:46; cf. Luke\'s additional prayer accounts). The priestly intercession of Christ is always present behind his ministry. Hebrews 7:25 ("he always lives to intercede for them") makes explicit what Mark shows in practice: the interceding Christ sustains his own mission through prayer to the Father.</p>',
    "47": '<p>A theme of the disciples in difficulty between the ascension and the return: "the boat was in the middle of the lake, and he was alone on land." The disciples rowing against the wind without Jesus present is a parable of the church in the world between Christ\'s departure and return — laboring, straining at the oars, the wind against them, Christ apparently absent. The image will have been recognized by Mark\'s community (ca. 65-70 CE, facing Neronian persecution): the church strains against opposition while Christ is "alone on land" — interceding (v.46), observing (v.48), and coming.</p>',
    "48": '<p>A direct revelation of Christ walking on water as divine theophany: "he went out to them, walking on the lake." Job 9:8 ("he alone treads on the waves of the sea") and Psalm 77:19 ("your path led through the sea, your way through the mighty waters") both apply this attribute to God alone. The phrase "he was about to pass by them" (<em>parerchomai</em>) echoes the divine "passing by" of Exodus 33:19-22 and 1 Kings 19:11 — God\'s theophanic self-revelation to Moses and Elijah. Jesus walking on water and "passing by" is not an incidental miracle but a deliberate enactment of the divine name.</p>',
    "49": '<p>A theme of failed recognition of the divine Christ: "they thought he was a ghost" (<em>phantasma</em>) — the disciples see Christ walking on water and mistake him for an apparition. The failure to recognize the divine Christ is a consistent pattern in Mark: the disciples fail to understand the feedings (6:52, 8:17-21), the transfiguration (9:6), the passion predictions (8:32-33, 9:32, 10:35-41). The ghost-misidentification is the extreme form of the general failure of perception that Jesus will diagnose with "do you have eyes but fail to see?" (8:18).</p>',
    "50": '<p>A direct revelation of the divine self-identification: "Take courage! It is I. Don\'t be afraid" — the Greek <em>egō eimi</em> (I am) is the LXX rendering of the divine name YHWH in Exodus 3:14 ("I AM WHO I AM") and the formula of divine self-identification in Isaiah 43:10-11 ("I am he"; "I am the LORD"). When Jesus says <em>egō eimi</em> in the context of walking on water (divine attribute, Job 9:8) in a theophanic passing-by (Exod 33; 1 Kgs 19), the declaration is not mere identification ("it\'s me, not a ghost") but theophanic self-disclosure: the God of Exodus is walking toward them on the water.</p>',
    "51": '<p>A revelation of Christ\'s authority over creation: "the wind died down" — as in 4:39, the stilling of the sea by Christ\'s presence and word demonstrates the divine authority over the waters that the OT consistently attributes to YHWH (Ps 89:9: "You rule over the surging sea; when its waves mount up, you still them"; Ps 107:25-29: "he commanded and stirred up a tempest... he stilled the storm to a whisper"). "They were completely astonished" — the proper response to an encounter with the divine, which is consistently expressed through astonishment in Mark (1:27, 2:12, 5:42, 6:51).</p>',
    "52": '<p>A revelation of the disciples\' hardened hearts as the obstacle to Christological understanding: "they had not understood about the loaves; their hearts were hardened." The feeding miracle had been the sign that should have taught them who Jesus is (the wilderness provider, the new Moses, the bread of life), but they had not understood. The hardened heart is the theological explanation for the disciples\' persistent failure of perception — the same language used for Pharaoh (Exod 4:21; 7:3) and for Isaiah\'s diagnosis of Israel (Isa 6:10; Mark 4:12). The disciples are not yet free from the hardness that the cross and resurrection will crack open.</p>',
    "53": '<p>A theme of Christ\'s return to the needs of the crowd after private prayer: landing at Gennesaret and immediately being recognized — the privacy of the mountain prayer (v.46) gives way to the press of public ministry. The pattern of withdrawal and return is the rhythm of the incarnate life: prayer to the Father, ministry to the people, prayer again. It is the rhythm Christ commends to his disciples (6:31) and lives himself.</p>',
    "54": '<p>A theme of immediate recognition and response: "as soon as they got out of the boat, people recognized Jesus" — the news of Jesus has spread throughout Galilee so that his arrival is immediately recognized and responded to. The recognition is not the theological recognition of faith ("you are the Christ") but practical recognition of the healer — they know what he does and run to bring the sick. Even partial recognition that Jesus can help leads people to him; the fuller revelation of who he is comes as they engage with him.</p>',
    "55": '<p>A theme of the urgency of coming to Christ with the sick and suffering: "they ran throughout that whole region and carried the sick on mats to wherever they heard he was." The urgency — running, carrying, going wherever he is — is the response that the gospel demands. The picture of people carrying the helpless to the one who heals is an enacted parable of intercession: those who can move bring those who cannot to the one who restores. The community of faith carries the sick to Christ in prayer.</p>',
    "56": '<p>A direct fulfillment of the Isaiah-35 signs: "all who touched even the edge of his cloak were healed" — universal healing, no exception, no one turned away. The hemorrhaging woman\'s touch (5:28) has become the pattern for the whole region: touching the edge of the cloak, and healing. Isaiah 35:5-6 promised that in the age of eschatological restoration, the blind will see, the deaf hear, the lame leap, the mute sing. The marketplaces of Gennesaret — packed with the sick who touch Jesus\'s cloak and are healed — are the fulfillment of Isaiah\'s vision of the messianic age. Christ\'s presence is the presence of the promised time of healing.</p>'
  }
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-christ', 'mark')
    merge_comm(existing, MARK)
    save_comm('mkt-christ', 'mark', existing)
    total = sum(len(v) for v in existing.values())
    print(f'Mark mkt-christ chs 5-6: {total} verses total written.')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
